'''Band VI''' is a [[radio frequency]] range within the [[super high frequency]] (SHF) part of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]].<ref name="ukbb1">{{cite web|url=http://theskywaves.demon.co.uk/UK_BROADCASTING_BANDS.pdf|title=UK BROADCASTING BANDS|date=2003-01-01|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher=TheSkywaves.NET}}</ref><ref name="unesco1">{{cite web|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0007/000749/074953eb.pdf|title=Latest statistics on radio and television broadcasting|year=1987|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher=UNESCO, Division of Statistics on Culture and Communication Office of Statistics}}</ref><ref name="bbc1">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/rd/pubs/reports/1972-10.pdf|title=SATELLITE BROADCASTING: A ZONED REFLECTOR AERIAL FOR THEDOMESTIC RECEPTION OF BAND VI|year=1972|accessdate=2009-05-20|publisher=BBC Research & Development}}</ref>

One source states that Band VI ranges from 11.7 to 12.5 [[GHz]],<ref name="ukbb1" /> whilst other earlier sources state the range as 11.7 to 12.7&nbsp;GHz.<ref name="unesco1" /><ref name="bbc1" /> The band is used for [[Direct-broadcast satellite|direct-broadcast satellite (DBS)]]<ref name="ukbb1" />  and amateur [[radio astronomy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://groups.google.com/group/sara-list/web/radioastronomy-with-a-small-12ghz-satellitedish|title=radioastronomy with a small 12GHz satellitedish  
